isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.60) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.26. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (95% CI [12.97, 14.09], t(826) = 47.67, p < .001). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, 95% CI [-0.92, 0.66], t(826) = -0.32, p = 0.749; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.46, 95% CI [-3.08, -1.83], t(826) = -7.71, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.55, 95% CI [-0.69, -0.41])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.86, 95% CI [-3.52, -2.19], t(826) = -8.45, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.64, 95% CI [-0.79, -0.49])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.96, 95% CI [-3.90, -2.02], t(826) = -6.16, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.66, 95% CI [-0.87, -0.45])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.05, 95% CI [-4.05, -2.06], t(826) = -6.00, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.68, 95% CI [-0.91, -0.46])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
